msIdentifier.collection: John Frederick Lewis Collection of European Manuscripts

msContents.summary: This manuscript is a twelfth-century Spanish monastic copy of Augustine's Enarrationes in Psalmos (Psalms 119-133), a commentary on the Psalms for preachers, followed by Augustine's Enchiridion, a treatise on Christian piety. The Enchiridion is prefaced by the paragraph from Augustine's Retractio about the treatise. The manuscript was held by the Abbey of Santa María de Benevívere in northern Spain, which was founded in 1169 and followed the Augustine Rule. The text is written in Protogothic script with rubrication in red and approximately fifteen large initials in combinations of red, yellow, and blue. Corrections and additions are written in the margins throughout. A bifolium bound in at the end presents variations of ornamental initials in black ink, A-F and L-N, with four to six variations of each letter. On the second verso of the bifolium, fifteenth-century reader Brother Hugo has copied the hymn Veni, Sancte Spiritus, and a version of the collect following the Salve Regina that appears in Spanish missals, signing his name at the end (Ugo Frey).

binding.p: Contemporary binding; pigskin over oak boards, with worm damage; groove for clasp is visible on the front cover; spine reinforced in early twentieth century; binding partially detached

origin.p: Second half of the twelfth century

history.provenance: Abbey of Santa María de Benevívere (Spain, twelfth century; ex libris of the monastery: "hec est liber s[an]c[t]e marie de beneuiuere qui abstulerit anathema sit, Amen, am[en] amen," fol. 180v); Brother Hugo (prayer written in fifteenth-century hand and signed, last leaf verso); William Bragge (sold 1876); Gerald E. Hart, Montreal (sold 1890); George Dunn of Woolley Hall (sold 1913, bookplate inside front cover); John Frederick Lewis, Philadelphia (pencil note by Lewis inside back cover, "Sotheby's London 2/13/1913"; bookplate inside front cover); given by his widow, Anne Baker Lewis, to the Free Library of Philadelphia in 1936; armorial bookplate of an unidentified owner on the front inside cover includes a wolf or fox rampant below three six-pointed stars
